@node pinkulus "I, PINKULUS: Mouse in a Cat's Land"

@{fg fill}  If you like @{i}Animaniacs@{ui} or @{b}Pinky@{ub} or @{u}Stranger in a Strange Land@{uu},
then you'll love I, PINKULUS. The life story of Pinky the lab mouse.
This is the first part of many in the story of His life. @{"E-Mail" link main} me for more.
This story is/was being to the Usenet newsgroup alt.tv.animaniacs.@{fg text}

Here is the first part of the story of Pinky, the lab-mouse, as
received from his holy mouth into my *holy* head.



            I, PINKULUS: Mouse in a Cat's Land
            __________________________________
                   p a r t   o n e.1
            __________________________________


                  HIS MACULATE ORIGIN


                          i


ONCE UPON A TIME when the world was young there was a Mouse named
Smith.
    Valentine Pinkulus Smith was as real as taxes but he was a
race of one.
    The first rodentian expedition from termite Terra(ce) to Acme
Acres was selected ont he theory that the greatest danger to
mouse on earth was mouse himself. At that time only eight Terrace
years affter founding of the first rodentian colony on Loony, any
interoceanary trip made by mice necessarily had to be made in
weary free-for-all transits, doubly tangent semi-ellipses -- from
Terrace to Acme, two hundred fifty-eight days, the same for the
return journey, plus four hundred fifty-five days waiting at Acme
while the two continents crawled slowly back into daylight
savings time which would permit making a doubly-tanget transit
shortened by one Earth hour.
    Besides itswearing length, the trip was chancy. Only by
refueling at a pizza station, then tacking back almost into
Terra's city limits, could the primitive rolling coffin, the
Unvoy, make the trip at all. Once at Acme she might be able to
return -- if she did not crash at arrival, if water could be
found at Acme to fill her reaction-mouse tanks, if some sort of
food could be found at Acme, if a thousand other things did not
go wrong.
    But the physical danger was judged to be less important than
the p-sychological stresses. Eight mice, crowded together like
guinea pigs for almost three Terrace years, had better get along
much better than humans usually did. An all-male crew had been
vetoed as unhealthy and socially unstable from lessons learned
earlier. A ship's company of four married couples had been
decided as optimum, if the necassary specialties could in such a
combination.

---------- end part 1.1 -----------
@endnode
